() show newline
(Collective decisions require:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Privacy) show newline
(  * Voters shouldn't know how others voted) show newline
(  * Verifiability) show newline
(  * Results must be provably correct) show newline
(  * Coercion resistance) show newline
(  * Can't prove how you voted to others) show newline
(  * Availability) show newline
(  * Voting continues despite failures) show newline
() show newline
(Voting systems that sacrifice any of these properties enable) show newline
(manipulation; true collective decision requires all four.) show newline
() show newline
(Traditional approaches fail:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Open ballot) show newline
(  * No privacy, enables coercion) show newline
(  * Trusted tallier) show newline
(  * Single point of compromise) show newline
(  * Secure multi-party computation) show newline
(  * Complex, high communication overhead) show newline
() show newline
(Each failure mode represents a fundamental architectural limitation, not) show newline
(merely an implementation weakness.) show newline
() show newline
(None of these approaches fits a decentralized, trustless environment.) show newline
() show newline
(Homomorphic encryption provides:) show newline
() show newline
(  * Vote on encrypted ballots) show newline
(  * Sum without decryption) show newline
(  * Decrypt only the final tally) show newline
(  * Mathematical proof of correctness) show newline
() show newline
(Homomorphic encryption resolves the apparent paradox: computing on data) show newline
(without seeing it.) show newline
